Stock tax declaration for Sweden - Guide

Published on 2025, April 11th

This guide reflects my understanding of how to declare taxes when selling shares / stock options in Sweden.

I assume no responsibility for any errors in the calculations provided by this tool or errors in the guide - also, none of what you find here is financial advice.

If you consider this work valuable, I always accept espressos - or, by using the referred links to join Revolut / Wise and we’ll both get a small bonus - for free! :)

All the operations done in “The practice” section are done through THE COMPANION SPREADSHEET - I highly recommend you first read The theory first, and then head to the practice. Boring, right?

The theory

Understanding: Stock Options vs RSU vs Shares

Before diving into taxes, let’s first distinguish between Stock Options (ATM/OTM), Restricted Stock Units (RSUs), and regular shares. In all cases, you are only required to declare them after selling them — when you realize a profit.

Stock Options (ATM/OTM):
These do not represent ownership of the stocks. Instead, your employer grants you the option to purchase them at a fixed price (called the grant price). To sell them, you must first “acquire” them through a process called exercise.

Restricted Stock Units (RSUs):
RSUs are, in essence, shares you already own. When you sell them, you are required to declare the transaction. Note that your employer typically withholds a portion of the RSUs (around 52% of the total pool) to cover income tax obligations.

Shares:
These refer to shares you may have purchased manually, outside of your stock plan. For tax purposes, they function the same as RSUs.

More information on this topic (in Swedish) on this page.

If you have exercised stock options (ATM/OTM)

If you’ve exercised stock options, either by buying them with your own money (sell-to-cover) or through a same-day sale (most likely the latter), your employer has already:

  1. Declared the operation (listed as “Benefit option” on your payslip).
  2. Paid part of the taxes to Skatteverket by deducting them from your salary.

If the tax amount exceeds what your salary can cover, your monthly salary will be 0 kr, and you’ll need to pay the remaining balance to Skatteverket by February 12th of the following year.

To check how much you owe, look for an entry on your payslip labeled “Tax owed to SKV by EE”.

Usually, exercises made between the 1st and 10th of a month appear on the same month’s payslip, while exercises made between the 11th and the last day of the month are reported in the following month’s payroll.

If you have sold

You might wonder: if the employer already declared the exercise, what’s your responsibility?

You must declare the sale operation you performed, even if the profit is zero or negative, by filling out the K4 form.

You’ll pay an additional 30% tax on the difference between the sell price and the average acquisition cost.

Please note that a “same-day sale” consists of two operations combined: an exercise followed by a sale at the same Fair Market Value (FMV).

An example of a sale

Imagine you’re in the situation of having done a same-day sale of 10 stock options (ATM/OTM) when the price was 100$; these stock options grant price was 50$.

The total amount got from the market on this operation is 10 * 100$ = 1000$; but since they are stock options (you have the option to buy them), eTrade must first buy them at 50$ (your original grant price); therefore you actually gained 1000$ - (10 * 50$) = 500$.

These 500$ are taxed at income level (~56%) and your company is declaring them for you, therefore your total net gain is = (1 - 0.56) * 500$ = 220$

A same-day sale is actually an exercise + sale; Skatteverket has already been informed about the exercise, but you must declare the sale in the K4.

A sale is composed of 2 values; the sale value (Försäljningspris) and the buy value (Omkostnadsbelopp); what we call the capital gain is the difference between sale and buy. The sale value you’re going to declare is 1000$ converted to SEK; but things get complicated when you have to calculate the buy value .

Skatteverket wants to know what’s the average cost for all your shares of that company; so imagine you received 1 RSU for 90$ and another 1 RSU for 95$; it turns out that you must take into account these 2 RSU in the sale as well, because that’s affecting the total acquisition cost of the shares you just sold.

(Little caveat here: your company most likely awarded you X shares per month but you actually only receive (X * 0.48), rounded to closest integer and the rest as cash in your payslip; that’s because half of those have been auto-sold before you received it to cover for income taxation; Skatteverket confirmed us that in the calculation of the average you input the share you received, not the one you got granted).

Let’s try to find our buy value:

Total cost = 10 ATM * 100$ (stock options bought) + 1 RSU * 90$ + 1 RSU * 95$ = 1185$
Total shares = 10 + 1 + 1 = 12
Average acquisition cost = 1185$ / 12 = 98.75$

So our Acquisition cost is not 100$, it’s actually a bit lower because we had some RSU that lowered down the total value!

How many shares did we sell? 10 * 98.75$ = 987,5$ is our buy value (Omkostnadsbelopp).

Capital gain therefore will be 1000$ (Försäljningspris) - 987,5$ (Omkostnadsbelopp) = 12.5$

… and yes, Skatteverket wants you to declare this and pay them 30% of 12.5$ = 3.75$

What exchange rate (FX) to use when declaring?

Skatteverket requires all amounts in Swedish Kronor (SEK), but you received USD!

As a general rule, if a transaction has been made during a bank holiday, you must use the closest available rate in the past - this means, if you received some RSU during a Sunday, put the rate that USDSEK had on the Friday when the market closed.

As for the FX to use, the rule here is:

If you kept the USDs for more than 30 days after selling shares

Use the exchange rate (FX) on the transaction date from the Riksbanken official source - the spreadsheet already calculates this for you automatically based on the date you put.

When you eventually convert your USD to SEK (if you do), you must report any gain or loss on the next year.
Use the average acquisition cost method to calculate this and report it in K4 section C - a separate sheet is available to help with these calculations.

If you converted USDs to SEKs within 30 days

Use the actual exchange rate (FX) you received during the conversion to calculate the “Försäljningspris” for the K4. The sheet includes a “Sell FX” column to assist with this.

As only the proceeds you received must be taken into account in the FX gain/losses, and not the entire sale your report (this is a problem when we’re dealing with stock options), make sure you put the “Grant Price” in the sale row so that the spreadsheet can calculate everything correctly.

The practice

Now that we got through the basic theory,, what you want to do first is cloning THE COMPANION SPREADSHEET.

A word of caution: Working with spreadsheets it’s tedious and time consuming, and also prone to human errors.

If you are not confident enough in your spreadsheet skills, you could instead give a try to https://www.skatteguru.se/ that will let you upload the PDFs from eTrade and do all the work for you. But, if you’re a psycho like me and still like to see scary numbers all day, please continue reading.

A mistake that can frequently happen is that the formulas refer to non-existent references or that, when adding rows, they don’t retain any formulas.

To make sure that all the cells have the correct formulas, highlight the first row of the colored cells (to understand, from L2 to AE2), then mouse-grab the dot in the bottom-right corner and pull it down until the end of the sheet (vertically).
This will ensure that all the formulas are correct.

Step 1 - Add a row for each RSU vested or share you bought

If you don’t have RSUs packages, never exercised stocks or manually bought shares of this company, you can skip this step!

What we must do is add the RSUs you received from your employer throughout the years, or the shares of this company you bought (if any).

Check your broker (in eTrade, go to your holdings, open “Restricted Stock”, and for each of these releases, add a row in the spreadsheet).For more information about each release, click “View confirmation of release” PDF.

A little shortcut

I highly recommend you to do this manually - but in case you want a shortcut, I have a little javascript you can just use; make sure you first open all your RSU grants, then copy and paste this in the DevTools. The code is going to extract all the information and download a CSV that you can directly copy paste in the spreadsheet, no edits needed.
This thing only works if we’re not in a blackout period, otherwise the grants show “0” as vested RSUs.

(() => { const hs = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('[data-test-id="RSblockdetails"] > table > tbody')).map(r => { const cs = r.querySelector("tr").querySelectorAll("td"), ds = cs[2].innerText.split("/"), d = new Date(`${ds[2]}-${ds[0]}-${ds[1]}`); return { d, s: `${d.getDate()}/${d.getMonth()+1}/${d.getFullYear()}`, q: +cs[3].innerText, p: +cs[5].innerText.replace("$","") }; }).sort((a, b) => a.d - b.d);
const csv = hs.map(r => [r.s, r.s, "RSU vesting", r.q, r.p].join(",")).join("\n");
const url = URL.createObjectURL(new Blob([csv], { type: "text/csv" })); const a = Object.assign(document.createElement("a"), { href: url, download: "rsu.csv" }); a.click();URL.revokeObjectURL(url); })();

Now that we have identified where to find the RSU vested, you want, for each of this RSU received, add a row in the spreadsheet with the following data:

Date: the day when the share was released
FX Date: put the same date initially. If the cell becomes red, double click on this cell and set it to the closest day in the past until it’s not read anymore. (This happens because shares can be released on a bank holiday, and we won’t have a USDSEK rate to use)
Operation: “RSU vesting”
Qty: the quantity of RSUs you received. This should match the number you see in the screenshot below under “Sales Blocked Shares Qty”; or "Shares issued" in the “Confirmation of Release PDF”.
FMV: Must match “Est. Cost Basis per share”, or “Market Value Per Share” in the “Confirmation of Release PDF”

Note: if you have multiple RSU packages you’ve received during these years, you can sum each RSU you received for the month as long as their FMV matches - or add separate rows - it’s the same!
Note 2: You need to add the RSU you’ve received since the beginning, not only for this year.
Note 3: If you have manually bought shares of Spotify, you must add them as well with the same process (use “Buy” as an operation to differentiate them).

Step 2 - Add a row for each sale

Perfect! Now we must add any sale you did.

Find all the sales you did (in eTrade, go to Your orders, and select the tax year you’re interested in (for 2025 declaration, you would look for 2024); then filter for “Executed”; then start from the oldest one). For more details about the order, expand the row and click “View confirmation of Exercise” PDF.

The order type is either going to be “Same-Day Sale” or “Sell Restricted Stock”.

When “Order Type” is “Same-Day Sale”

You’ll need to add 2 rows, one for “Exercise” and one for “Sell”.

First row of exercise

Date: Must be “Order Date”
FX Date: same as “Order Date”; since you can’t sell when market is closed, you don’t need the same trick you used for RSU vesting
Operation: “Exercise”
Qty: Must be “Exercised Qty”
FMV: Must be “Execution Price”; or “Sale Price” in the “Confirmation of Exercise”.
Fees: Add the fixed SEC fee of ~10$ (check the PDF for the precise figure) in order to match the proceeds you received.
Override FX: Do not populate this value for exercise.
Grant Price: Must be “Grant Price” in the “Confirmation of Exercise” - useful to calculate income tax and correct FX gains/losses.
Net on eTrade docs: Must be “Net Proceeds” in $ in the “Confirmation of Exercise” - useful to calculate that eTrade didn’t mess up.

Now locate the payslip received from your employer (if the order was made before the 10th of month, it will be in the same month payslip; check next month otherwise), and, populate like this:
Benefit Options: Put the amount found in Benefit Options E000XXXX
Tax owed to SKV by EE: Put the amount found in “Tax owed to SKV by EE” (or similar)

Second row of sell

Date, FX Date, FMV, Net on eTrade docs, Grant Price: same as the Exercise row above
Qty: Must be “Sold Qty”, but in negative
Operation: “Sell”
Fees: Add any fee you encountered during this operation. eTrade fixed fees are: 9.99$ SEC fee, ~0.25$ brokerage fee; and, when you withdraw the money, 25$ fee. If you did multiple orders and then only one withdrawal, what I personally do is add the 25$ wire fee in the last sale.
Sell FX USDSEK: When your exchange from USD to SEK was made within 30 days of the transaction date, you have to use the FX you got when converting (the one your bank gave you). This is a simplification from SKV in order to declare the correct amount you received in SEK without the need to have another row in the K4/A for currency exchanges; this is called the 30 day rule. In order to correctly calculate the FX gain/losses and only taking into account the part you received, you must also set “Grant Price” correctly, otherwise the FX will be applied to whole sale, causing a non proportional distribution of the new FX. If you have not converted within 30 days, then you must add another entry in the K4/A; you can use the companion spreadsheet “USDSEK operations”.

When “Order Type” is “Sell Restricted Stock”

In this case, we’re talking about a sale of RSUs.

Date: Must be “Order Date”
FX Date: Same as “Order Date”
Operation: “Sell”
Qty: Must be “Sold Qty”, but in negative
FMV: Must be “Execution Price”.
Fees: Add any fee you encountered during this operation. eTrade fixed fees are: 9.99$ SEC fee, ~0.25$ brokerage fee; and, when you withdraw the money, 25$ fee. If you did multiple orders and then only one withdrawal, what I personally do is add the 25$ wire fee in the last sale.
Grant Price: 0$ - this sale is not referred to any stock option, therefore your grant price is 0$
Net on Etrade docs: Put the “Est. Net Proceeds” you see in eTrade
Sell FX USDSEK: When your exchange from USD to SEK was made within 30 days of the transaction date, you have to use the FX you got when converting (the one your bank gave you). This is a simplification from SKV in order to declare the correct amount you received in SEK without the need to have another row in the K4/A for currency exchanges; this is called the 30 day rule. In this case, you want to set 0$ (or leave empty) the Grant Price, in order to correctly calculate the FX on the whole sale. If you have not converted within 30 days, then you must add another entry in the K4/A; you can use the companion spreadsheet “USDSEK operations”.

Before February 12th of next year

Even though the declaration opens later in April, Skatteverket wants you to deposit the money to Skattekonto starting from February 12th of the next year after your sale, otherwise they’re going to start charging you interest.

The interest percentage is considerably little, we’re talking about 2.5% yearly (as 2025) on the amount you owe them, minus 30’000kr (the interest changes every year, by the way); this means that if you owe them ~28’000$, they could charge you ~625$ if you don’t pay for an entire year; if, you pay 1 month after the deadline, that will be ~51$ in total.

If you don’t want to be charged, all you have to do is deposit the amount you owe them before February 12th; the question is, of course: how do you know how much you owe Skatteverket?

Once you have populated the spreadsheet completely, just sum the column K (Payslip: Tax owed to SKV by EE) and the column Q (Taxes to pay on capital gain when selling) for this year, and you’ll get a more-or-less (check notes on why more-or-less) precise figure on how much to deposit.

In order to deposit the money, head to Skattekonto, log-in via BankID, and you’ll find the OCR payment information on the right sidebar. Usually, they are always BankGiro: 5050-1055 and your complete person-number as OCR reference number; make a payment from your bank and you’re settled.

FAQ

What if I deposit more than I should?

No problem! When the declaration is settled later that year, you can withdraw the extra money back to your bank. Also, you’ll earn some interest on this deposited amount, so it’s a win-win.

What if I deposit less than I should?

They will charge you interest, retroactively, on the difference you owe them between February 12th and when you deposit the money.

Last year I deposited X but I actually needed only to deposit Y (with Y < X)?

This is very common, because the money you received from eTrade is taxed at a 54% lump-sum taxation rate (it was 57% until 2024), which is higher than the one it’s going to be used at the end, which has an average of ~52%; therefore, what happens is that when declaration s settled you’ll get the difference back.

Is that all?

Additionally, you may want to:

  • Add the taxes that your ISK reported automatically (on Avanza, you can find them here - must do 30% of the Schablonintäkt)
  • If you sold an apartment, add any possible taxes from a sale of an apartment
  • If you have side businesses, add any possible taxes on extra-income you have received
  • If you own an apartment, maybe remove 30% of the interest from your mortgage (and 21% on amounts over 100’000kr)
  • If you want to keep it simple, just add, never subtract :)

Time to declare

When tax season begins, head to Skatteverket’s website and access “Inkomstdeklaration 1” to complete your declaration.

Now, click “Bilagor” and find “Försäljning av värdepapper m.m. (K4)” and then click on “A. Marknadsnoterade aktier, aktieindexobligationer, aktieoptioner m.m”; this is how you access the K4/A form.


Fill the form with what you got as a result of the sheet form from the columns “K4/A”:

And then finalise your form and send it by clicking “Skicka in”.

SKV automatically calculates the taxes you owe them based on the difference between the “winning” and the “buy” price. These values should match the “Taxes to pay on capital gain” column in the spreadsheet.

And that’s it folks - pay with Swish/BankGiro the remaining amount and you’re done.

How to convert USD to SEK

After you’re done with the transaction on Etrade, you need to transfer your proceeds in USD to your bank.
I strongly discourage you from transferring them to your classic Swedish bank like SEB, Nordea, etc… as they don’t provide a good exchange rate (FX), and you’ll end up losing a big chunk of money.

If you’re going to do multiple transactions within the same month, I recommend you to always cash in E-Trade and subsequently transfer them later, to avoid the inevitable 25$ fee that comes with every wire transfer.

When to convert them? As the market fluctuates, it’s difficult to give a precise answer. However, if you convert your USD to SEK within 30 days of the sale, you don’t need to declare any additional FX gain or loss. This allows you some flexibility to potentially optimize your conversion by setting a limit order and taking a small gamble. 😊

Revolut / Wise

Revolut and Wise are practically the same, and they offer the best FX on the market.

When exchanging more than 1000$, you’ll encounter a fee. You should consider waiving the fee by buying the Premium version of their service, as it’s well worth the cost (the fee could be more than the Premium), and you’ll also have additional benefits, like free NordVPN or Wolt. In order to do this:

Find your Revolut details: open Revolut, click on Accounts, add a USD account by clicking “Add new \> Currency account” and select “US Dollar”. Now that you have a USD account, click “Details” and you’ll find the SWIFT code and the Bank Account number.

Once you’ve received your USD in Revolut (it should take around 1 day), you want to convert them to SEK.

Avanza AF with manual USD FX

Any AF account on Avanza has an additional feature that can be added that will allow you to keep USD and manually convert them later; this service comes for free and the FX is the best one you can find (slightly better than the one above). In order to make Avanza manual exchange to work you need to follow few steps:

  1. Obviously you need an Avanza account if you don’t have it already. You can create the account online, however you might have to send some documents signed by two people living in Sweden to verify your identity. The documents should be sent by regular post and it might take a few days for them to approve.
    1. Then you need to open a “Aktie & fondkonto” (stock and fund account). ISK does not have manual currency exchange unfortunately. You can open the account with a few clicks and it’s instant.
    2. Deposit some money to the account as it’s needed for the next step.
    3. Apply for a credit. Go to “Spara & Investera -> Värdepapperskredit” and ask for a credit on your account. It might take a few days for the credit to be approved.
    4. Buy some securities (low risk funds maybe) in the account. Without having any securities, they will not approve your manual currency exchange.
    5. Go to Profile and write a new message to them, ask them to enable USD and manually exchange currency in the account. It might take a few days for this to show up.
    6. Deposit money to your account. You can find transfer information here. As it also mentioned in the link, It’s important to add the account number to receiver information in etrade so Avanza knows where to put your money.
    7. They might send a message and ask you for some documents proving the money is yours and it comes from a legitimate source.
    8. Steps a to f needs to happen just once, after that you can transfer your money with ease and benefit from a very good exchange rate.
    9. Go to this page to exchange

Where to keep the tax money until next year

Most likely, you’ll need to save a chunk of this money for next year's declaration; for this reason, I recommend you to put them in a safe place like a savings account that gives you interest; just stay up to date on what’s better by checking this comparison website - choose the one that best fits your situation.

I usually don’t recommend fixed interest saving accounts to people, but for the tax money this may be an exception, as keeping them for 6 months could give you a very good rate and you know for sure that you don’t want to spend this money.

Don’t put the money you owe Skatteverket in risky stuff like stocks, you need to withdraw them next year!

An alternative to Swedish savings accounts if you want to keep the USD is using an USD-based saving account which, most of the time, offers higher interest rate than swedish banks - but please note that once you use any non-Swedish bank, you need to report the interest received yourself; this can be done in the section 7.2 (Ränteinkomster, utdelningar m.m) and must be converted to SEK.

This method is a bit more risky, as you’ll expose yourself to the USDSEK/FX volatility; and it will be a pain to declare these the next year, as you will need to declare the interest rate earned throughout the year and convert it to SEK, and declare the possible win/losses caused by the late FX conversion; but it may be worth it economically.
